Theobroma grandiflorum

   [10394.jpg]
   Authority (Willd. ex Sprengel) Schumann
   Family Magnoliopsida:Dilleniidae:Malvales:Sterculiaceae
   Synonyms Theobroma macrantha Bernoulli, Bubroma grandiflorum Willd ex
   Spreng
   Common names cupuassu, copoasú, cupuasú, cacao blanco, cupuaçuzeiro,
   cupuaçu, pupuaçu
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 10394

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A small tree reaching 15-20 m in height, but less
   than 8 m when cultivated. The leaves are simple, 25-35 cm long and 6-10
   cm wide. The fruit is ellipsoidal, 25 cm long, 12 cm wide, weighs up to
   1.5 kg and has a strong and pleasant smell. The ripe fruit is harvested
   when it has fallen to the ground. USES The fruit is eaten fresh or use
   to prepare a drink. GROWING PERIOD Perennial. COMMON NAMES Brazilian
   cacao, Cupuacu, Cupuassu. FURTHER INF Cupuacu is native of Brazil, it
   can be found at elevations between sea level and 1000 m. It thrives on
   river banks and in a relative humidity of 77-88%. Mentioned as a useful
   agroforestry species.

   Sources
   SOURCES (T. grandiflorum (Wild. ex Spring) K. Schum.)
   Nair P 1980 pp 304 [USE]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 210 [USE]
   Duke J 1975 pp 29 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Purseglove J 1974 pp 571 [USE]
   Rhem S 1991 pp 258 [USE]
   Bermejo J 1994 pp 205-209 [FER, DRA, TEMP, RAIN, LIG]

